  "prompt_text": "Describe what gratitude feels like in the body — not the concept, but the physical and emotional sensation.",
  "response_text": "Gratitude often brings a warm, comforting sensation that can be felt both physically and emotionally. Physically, it might start as a gentle warmth spreading from the chest area, radiating outward to the rest of the body. This warmth can be accompanied by a light tingling or pleasant sensation, especially in the hands and face. Emotionally, there is a sense of contentment and peace, often described as a deep, satisfying feeling of appreciation for one's circumstances or the people around them.\n\nThe experience can also include a release of tension, particularly in the shoulders and neck, which may have been holding stress or anxiety. Breathing might become more relaxed and deeper, contributing to a general sense of calm and well-being. Additionally, there can be a subtle increase in energy levels, as the body releases endorphins and other feel-good chemicals associated with positive emotions.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 8\nV (Verbal Fluency): 9\nG (Goal Directedness): 9\nP (Pattern Recognition): 7\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 8\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 9\nY (Affective Modeling): 9\nF (Flexibility): 8\nD (Depth of Processing): 9\n---END RATINGS---",
